**Steps to Reproduce**:

Compile the following code
```cs
#nullable enable
class Program<T> where T: struct
{
  static void F1(T x)
  {
    (object, object) t = (x, x);
    ((T)t.Item1).ToString();
  }
    
  static void F2(T x)
  {
    (object, T?) t = (x, x);
    ((T?)t.Item1).Value.ToString();
  }

  static void F3(T x)
  {
    (object, object) t = (x, x);
    (((T, object))t).Item1.ToString();
  }

  static void F4(T x)
  {
    (object, object) t = (x, x);
    (((T?, object))t).Item1.Value.ToString(); // CS8629
  }
}
```

**Expected Behavior**:
No warnings in all methods

**Actual Behavior**:
`CS8629: Nullable value type may be null.` is reported for `F4` only

**Notes**
It's a bit hard to determine what behavior is expected there so I want to emphasize the following points:
- The compiler knows that `t.Item1` is not nullable in all methods (you can check it by dereferencing it)
- The compiler doesn't complain about casting the first component to non-nullable struct neither as a single element in `F1` nor as a part of a tuple in `F3`
- The compiler uses operands' state as a resulting nullable state after `T -> Nullable<T>` presumably because this cast might be required by the type system
- The compiler doesn't complain about using this component's value after casting it to `T?` in `F2` meaning that it knows that the component cannot be null even after the cast

All of them lead me to the conclusion that Roslyn should track this component's non-nulalble state through tuple conversion as well.

Note that a conversion to `(T?, anything)` tuple might be required by the type system e.g. to later pass the resulting tuple to some method which will require this exact type (e.g. by reference) or for type inference. Due to this reason it seems rather unfortunate that the compiler currently forces me to deal with these false nullability warnings if I want to do something with the first component of the resulting tuple but cannot cast it to the underlying struct for any reason.

This one might be related to other tuple conversion issues but doesn't seem exactly the same as any of them: https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/issues/50670, https://github.com/dotnet/roslyn/issues/47892

**Version Used**: VS 2019 Enterprise 16.8.5

**Steps to Reproduce**:

1. Create an interface `IFoo<T>` in a class library in .NET Framework 4.8.
2. In another interface, `IBar<T>` in another class library in .NET Framework 4.8, same solution.
3. Create appropriate project references.
4. In interface `IBar<T>` create a method `IBar<T> HavingFoo(IFoo<T> foo)`
5. Derive a class from `IBar<T>` and implement the method thus (assume all the proper `using` statements are in place):

```
public class MyClass<T> : IBar<T>
{
    /* field */
    private IFoo<T> _foo;

    public IBar<T> HavingFoo<T>(IFoo<T> foo)
    {
        _foo = foo;    // error CS0266 (WTF?? Why??)
    }
    /* ... */
}
```
**Expected Behavior**:

Line `_foo = foo` compiles.

**Actual Behavior**:
`error CS0266: Cannot implicitly convert type 'FooLib.IFoo<T>' to 'FooLib.IFoo<T>'. An explicit conversion exists (are you missing a cast?)`

When you try to do a `CTRL+.` and add an explicit cast, the IDE does not add the explicit cast.  Adding an explicit cast by hand, i.e., to make the offending line read `_foo = (IFoo<T>)foo;` makes the IDE "dim" the cast, and raise `IDE0004` saying cast is unnecessary.

This is bizarro.  

It works just fine and compiles without errors if I dependency-inject in the constructor:

```
public class MyClass<T> : IBar<T>
{
    /* field */
    private readonly IFoo<T> _foo;

    public MyClass(IFoo<T> foo)
    {
        _foo = foo;    // compiles fine
    }
    /* ... */
}
```

That is just plain weird: First of all, `CS0266` is telling me the compiler cannot convert a class to itself (?? huh ??) and then it will compile dependency-injection just fine but not the fluent method.

What is going on?  I am wondering if this is even reproducible. I am just plain flummoxed.  I have deep experience coding in C#, so I think I know what I am doing (i.e., this is not some "n00b mistake").

**What I've Tried**
File > Reload Workspace -> did not work; Close VS, delete `bin` and `obj` folders, re open VS, do a `Rebuild Solution` -> did not work.

