**Steps to Reproduce**:
Add the following code to a file in an empty project:

    public struct S { }

    public class C : IEqualityComparer<S>
    {

    }

Now use the Implement Interface feature on IEqualityComparer.

**Expected Behavior**:

I would expect the generated method signatures to be simply:

    public class C : IEqualityComparer<S>
    {
        public bool Equals(S x, S y) => throw new System.NotImplementedException();
        public int GetHashCode(S obj) => throw new System.NotImplementedException();
    }

**Actual Behavior**:
The behavior differs depending on the target framework of the containing project. Nullable=enable does not seem to be relevant.

For net5.0 the output is as follows:

    public class C : IEqualityComparer<S>
    {
        public bool Equals(S? x, S? y) => throw new System.NotImplementedException();
        public int GetHashCode([DisallowNull] S obj) => throw new System.NotImplementedException();
    }

For netcoreapp3.1 it looks like this:

    public class C : IEqualityComparer<S>
    {
        public bool Equals([AllowNull] S x, [AllowNull] S y) => throw new System.NotImplementedException();
        public int GetHashCode([DisallowNull] S obj) => throw new System.NotImplementedException();
    }

And for 4.8 it does what I would expect all of them to do:

    public class C : IEqualityComparer<S>
    {
        public bool Equals(S x, S y) => throw new System.NotImplementedException();
        public int GetHashCode(S obj) => throw new System.NotImplementedException();
    }

The net5.0 version doesn't even compile, because `bool Equals(S?, S?)` can't implement `bool Equals(S, S)`. The netcoreapp3.1 version compiles, but the [AllowNull] and [DisallowNull] attributes seem unnecessary.

